EDA Overivew¶

One of the most important steps to any data science experiment is Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA). EDA provides a first look at the data and is a critical in analyzing the data to understand and summarize its content. This is important to ensure the features fed into a ML algorithms are refined in order to get valid, correctly interpreted results.

EDA can be non-graphical or graphical. Each method can be applied to one variable/column (univariate) or a combination of variables (bivariate, multivariate).

A first step in any data scicence experiment is to understand the problem statement and the data before creating a model. This helps for gaining insights that will inform modeling choice and decisions.

The problem statement: Predict whether income exceeds $50K/yr based on census data. Also known as "Census Income" dataset. .

Remainder of this notebook provides coding examples of EDA for census data.

Load required libraries¶

Reading the data¶

  • Adult Dataset; the Cenus Income from the 1994 Census Database: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/adult
  • download link: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/adult/adult.data

Data description

  • age: continuous.
  • workclass: Private, Self-emp-not-inc, Self-emp-inc, Federal-gov, Local-gov, State-gov, Without-pay, Never-worked.
  • fnlwgt: continuous
  • education: Bachelors, Some-college, 11th, HS-grad, Prof-school, Assoc-acdm, Assoc-voc, 9th, 7th-8th, 12th, Masters, 1st-4th, 10th, Doctorate, 5th-6th, Preschool.
  • education-num: continuous.
  • marital-status: Married-civ-spouse, Divorced, Never-married, Separated, Widowed, Married-spouse-absent, Married-AF-spouse.
  • occupation: Tech-support, Craft-repair, Other-service, Sales, Exec-managerial, Prof-specialty, Handlers-cleaners, Machine-op-inspct, Adm-clerical, Farming-fishing, Transport-moving, Priv-house-serv, Protective-serv, Armed-Forces.
  • relationship: Wife, Own-child, Husband, Not-in-family, Other-relative, Unmarried.
  • race: White, Asian-Pac-Islander, Amer-Indian-Eskimo, Other, Black.
  • sex: Female, Male.
  • capital-gain: continuous.
  • capital-loss: continuous.
  • hours-per-week: continuous.
  • native-country: United-States, Cambodia, England, Puerto-Rico, Canada, Germany, Outlying-US(Guam-USVI-etc), India, Japan, Greece, South, China, Cuba, Iran, Honduras, Philippines, Italy, Poland, Jamaica, Vietnam, Mexico, Portugal, Ireland, France, Dominican-Republic, Laos, Ecuador, Taiwan, Haiti, Columbia, Hungary, Guatemala, Nicaragua, Scotland, Thailand, Yugoslavia, El-Salvador, Trinadad&Tobago, Peru, Hong, Holand-Netherlands.

Preprocessing and cleansing¶

Data preprocessing is a critical step in ML as the quality of data and the useful information derived from it directly affects the ability of our model to learn. These include the following:

  • Handling Null/Missing Values: easiest way is to remove all missing values, however it's not always the best approach as you could be losing valuable information that impacts your model, especially if your dataset is small.

      ** ways to handle missing data **
  - Drop these rows to exclude missing values in the data 
  - Replace with median/mean of values. Median may be better as it's unaffected by range/spread of data

  • Standardization: Creates a normalized scale for variables which are very different in scale. We transform values so the mean of the values is 0 and the standard deviation is 1. For example: given weight (kg) and age (years), if we don't standardize their values, weight will be given more weight/importance in our model given weight is much greater than age.

  • Handling Categorical Variables: Categorical variables have discreet values vs continous/numeric values. Often categories contain descriptions for values; eg: gender (male/female) or size (XL/L/M/S/XM). size is ordinal (it has an order (XL > L > S > XS), while gender is nominal (there is no order). To feed these types of categorial features into a model, requires they be converted to numeric representations using dummy-encoding, one-hot encoding, etc. The correct method to apply depends on whether it's nominal or ordinal.

  • Data Quality: To check for data quality issues, you can sample your data. For categorical variables, look at the range of possible values to ensure they make sense. If there are outliers, decide if they can be dropped depending on the nature of the outlier. They may be legitiate observatons and are sometimes the most interesting ones.

    ** ways to handle outliers **
- drop if the outlier is a mistake (eg: data entry)
- drop if the outlier creates a significant association that doesn't otherwise exist
- drop, if you have a lot of data and your sample wont be hurt by dropping a questionable outlier<br>

** simplify the data for use in modeling **
- Categorical variable with many levels (eg: many categories), decide whether some levels can be combined
- For multiple fields representing the same data, decide if one can be dropped or combined into a new field

Checking data quality

  • education-num vs education column: should we just keep 1?
  • capital-gain and capital-loss: we can sum up these into a new column "capital-gain-total" ?
  • education: we could combine some levels to reduce the number of categories
  • marital-status: similar to education, we could combine some categories to reduce the number
  • occupation: like education, we can combine some categories
  • working-class: like education, we can combine some
  • native-country: like education, we can combine some

Statistical Summary¶

Statistical summaries provide more information about the data. It provides insights such as the average, min, max values which helps to understand data distributions and trends as well as validate data.

  • statistical summary of all attributes
  • statistical summary of specific columns
  • statistics summary by group

statistical metrics

  1. Count: Number of observations for the variable
  2. Mean: Mean of all values for the variable
  3. Std: Standard deviation
  4. Min: Minimum value for the attribute
  5. Max: Maximum value for the attribute
  6. 25%: 25th percentile value in data
  7. 50%: 50th percentile value in data
  8. 75%: 75th percentile value in data

Custom Statistics¶

Pandas describe defaults to the statistics shown, but what if you wanted to add additional statistics? You can create a function for that as shown

In [78]:
def custom_describe(df):
    return pd.concat([df.describe().T,               # transpose
                      df.median().rename('median'),  # include median
                      df.skew().rename('skew'),      # include skewness
                      df.kurt().rename('kurt'),      # include kurtosis 
                     ], axis=1).T

custom_describe(data).round()  # round values

Data Visualization¶

Visualization using appropriate graphs helps our understanding of the data in a way that is often more inutitive and expressive than non-visual techniques. Univariant graphs are visualizations that describe a single varialbe while Multivariate shows relationships between multiple variables.

  • Visualize the most important or interesting attributes using appropriate techniques.
  • For each visualization, provide an interpretation as to why it is appropriate/interesting.
  • What does each visualization tell us?

Histogram (Univariate)¶

  • applies to numeric values
In [79]:
# histogram
data.hist(figsize=(12,10));

The visualization of the numerical attributes gives insights on the distribution of values.

  • Most individuals are age < 50 with max age around 90.
  • Most people have an education number 9, 10, 14 years
  • Most of the people work around 40 hrs per week. However there are a few who don't work and a few who work for almost 100 hours a week.
  • vast majority have few capital gains, but there are some outliers. Histogram is skewed right (eg: mean > median)

Explore the relationships among various attributes¶

  • Cross tabulations/contingency tables
  • Multivariate plots
  • Correlation heatmaps

We will plot pair plot to explore the pairwise relationship among attributes.

  • The diagonal shows histograms of each attribute (this is the default). You can specify a different value (eg: diagonal='kde') such as Kernel density estimation
  • In the other cells are the scatterplots (i.e. correlation plot) of each variable combination
In [85]:

# rotate labels

From the scatter plots, there looks to be little correlation between the variables

Correlation Analysis¶

Correlation is the statistical summary of the relationship between variables

  • Pearson's correlation for continuous values
    • Pearson correlation coefficient used to summarize the strength of the linear relationship between 2 data samples
    • value between -1 and 1 (full negative correlation to a full positive correlation), 0 means no correlation.
    • value below -0.5 or above 0.5 suggests a strong correlation; values below suggest weak correlation
In [87]:
# Compute the correlation matrix
corr = data.corr()
corr.style.background_gradient(cmap='coolwarm')

plt.title('Pearson Correlation of Features')
plt.yticks(rotation=45)
plt.xticks(rotation=45);

Correlation analysis is important for linear regression models. Here we decide on the prediction target (Eg: outcome or dependent variable) and what input features (predictor or independent variables) contribute to the prediction. We choose variables with the highest correlation between it and the target. If 2 predictor variables are also correlated (multicolinarity), we can decise to remove one of them.

  • not very strong correlations between the numeric features.
  • education-num: the strongest (+) correlation is between hours-per-week, net-capital-gains
